##Does an apple a day keep the doctor away?

What will an apple/day mean? Fruit consumed kgs/capita/year, cal from plant protein, calories from animal protein, calories from fat

What does keep the doctor away mean? It can mean dalys, cancer prevalence, depressive disorders, life expectancy.

My first question is: is our data normalized? Here I take steps to normalize the data from the columns where the skewness coefficient is not within the range (-0.6:0.6). I normalize the data by applying the sqrt() function and overwriting those same columns with excessive skew.

var <- select(df, -c(entity, total_pop, year, continent))
col <- data.frame(names(var))

var_skew <- data.frame(col, apply(var, 2, skewness, na.rm = TRUE)) 
print(var_skew)

skewed_bad <- filter(var_skew, !between(var_skew$apply.var..2..skewness..na.rm...TRUE., -0.6, 0.6))

skewed_bad$names.var.

df2 <- df
df2[,skewed_bad$names.var.] <- df2 %>% 
  select(skewed_bad$names.var.) %>% 
  apply(2, sqrt)

According to our data, the average life expectancy in 2019 was approximately 76 years. How well will production of apples (our strongest correlation to life expectancy) predict whether a person will live at least to 76?

df <- df %>% 
mutate("makes_avg" = case_when(life_expectancy >= 76 ~ TRUE,
                        TRUE~FALSE))
mod8<- glm(data = df,
              formula = makes_avg ~ kg_apple_prod_capita_year,
              family = "binomial")

df %>%
     add_predictions(mod8, type = "response") %>%
     ggplot(aes(x = kg_apple_prod_capita_year, y = pred)) +
     geom_smooth()

That is a perfect logistical curve if I’ve ever seen one! The more apples your country produces, the greater your chances of meeting an average life expectancy.

Overall, production of apples has a relatively large impact on life expectancy. I want to know if this is true for poor, medium, and affluent countries. Here I will divide GDP into 1/3s. The lower third I will classify as poor, the second third will be medium, and the upper third will be affluent. To start, I want to see if there are any differences in apple production between poor, medium, and affluent countries.

df <- df %>% 
  mutate("wealth" = case_when(gdp_capita_year < 38258.1 ~ "poor",
                            gdp_capita_year < 76516.18~ "medium",
                            TRUE ~ "rich"))
df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = wealth, y = kg_apple_prod_capita_year))+
  geom_col()

df %>%
     add_predictions(mod8, type = "response") %>%
     ggplot(aes(x = kg_apple_prod_capita_year, y = pred, color = wealth)) +
     geom_smooth()
